<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Broan is the most-installed range hood across LA — and the repair economics work differently than premium-only brands.</h2>

    <p>Broan-NuTone LLC is headquartered in Hartford, Wisconsin. The combined entity reflects 90+ years of US ventilation manufacturing: Henry Broan founded Broan in 1932 (the Motordor® Fan was the original product), J. Ralph Corbett founded NuTone in 1936 (originally door chimes), and the two companies merged in 1998. Manufacturing today runs across the US (Wisconsin), China (volume metalwork), Canada (Venmar air exchangers), and Italy (Best by Broan premium production). Sister brands within the Broan-NuTone LLC structure also include Aubrey Manufacturing (medicine cabinets), Rangaire (specialty professional-style hoods), and Best by Broan (Italian-designed premium tier).</p>

    <p>Broan's positioning differs from premium designer brands like Zephyr in ways that directly affect repair economics. Where Zephyr leans into design as a kitchen-aesthetic statement at $800-$5,000+ per unit, Broan's installed base is built on volume: builder relationships, retail availability at Home Depot and Lowe's, and entry-level pricing that puts a 40000 Series in nearly every apartment building, condo refurb, and mid-tier home in LA. Honest implication for repair: <strong>on entry-level 40000 Series units 8+ years old with motor failure, replacement is often cheaper than repair</strong> — replacement units retail $120-$150 versus $180-$280 for motor-only service. Mid-tier Allure ($200-$400) and premium Evolution ($400-$700) and Best by Broan ($600-$1,500) tip the math the other direction; repair almost always wins on those.</p>

    <p>This page covers the full Broan lineup we service — from 40000 Series workhorses to Evolution premium and Best by Broan, plus the legacy NuTone vintage units that still run in older LA homes — along with the LA neighborhood concentration patterns and the property-manager volume service angle that's unique to Broan in our service mix.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 SERIES COVERAGE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Broan lineup we service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Multiple tiers from mass-market to Italian premium, plus legacy NuTone.</h2>

    <p class="lead">40000 and 41000 Series cover mass-market volume installs. Allure, Evolution, and Best by Broan move up the tier ladder. Power Pack inserts handle custom hood applications. NuTone vintage covers legacy LA installations.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>40000 Series — Mass-Market Workhorse</h3>
        <p class="model-list">403004 (30" stainless) · 413004 (30" white) · 423604 (36" stainless) · multiple variants</p>
        <p>The most-installed Broan series across LA — apartment buildings, condo refurbs, mid-tier homes spec'd at builder grade. $80-$150 retail, basic two-speed fan, simple light. Common service: fan motor seizure at the 5-8 year mark (the most common Broan-specific failure pattern), two-speed switch wear from high-frequency use in active kitchens, light socket failures on older halogen units. We see 40000 Series motor failures almost predictably on the 6-7 year mark in LA apartment buildings — and property managers often replace the whole unit ($120-$150) rather than authorize a $180-$220 motor repair on an 8-year unit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>41000 Series — Convertible Ducted/Ductless</h3>
        <p class="model-list">41000 family · multiple variants</p>
        <p>Step up from 40000 — quieter operation (220 CFM versus 160 CFM on the basic 40000), convertible duct configuration. $100-$200 retail. Same fan motor failure patterns as 40000 but slightly longer typical lifespan (7-10 years). Common scenario we see: customer converted exhaust to recirculating during a kitchen renovation but never installed the charcoal filter required for recirculation mode. Cooking smells linger, customer thinks the hood is failing — actually the install was incomplete. $40-$60 charcoal filter plus 15-minute install resolves it. Not a repair, just installation completion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Allure® Series — Mid-Tier Stylish</h3>
        <p class="model-list">AR130SS · AR140SS · AR160SS · variants</p>
        <p>Style-focused mid-tier — Broan's response to consumer demand for more visually appealing range hoods at moderate price. $200-$400 retail. Common service: touchpad and electronic-control issues on newer Allure variants (more sophisticated electronics than basic 40000 Series), longer fan motor lifespan (8-12 years typical), occasional stainless surface dings that are cosmetic rather than repair scope. Allure repair-vs-replace math typically favors repair through year 8-10 because replacement costs run noticeably higher than entry-level 40000 Series.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Evolution Series — Premium Within Broan</h3>
        <p class="model-list">Evolution 1 · 2 · 3</p>
        <p>The quietest Broan offering, built around Quiet Hood™ and WhispAire® technologies that Broan documents as 40% quieter than traditional range hoods. $400-$700 retail — closest Broan gets to Zephyr/Best territory. Better motor specifications mean longer service life (10-15 years typical). Control board failures more common than on entry-level series because of the more sophisticated electronics. Whisper-technology motors are a different replacement spec from standard motors — substituting wrong is a common mistake by techs unfamiliar with the Evolution line.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Best by Broan — Italian Premium</h3>
        <p class="model-list">Italian-designed premium tier · multiple model lines</p>
        <p>$600-$1,500 retail — a different positioning entirely from mass-market Broan. Italian aesthetic and component sourcing, often mistaken in showrooms for Zephyr Designer Series tier despite being a separate brand. Limited LA installed base; mostly shows up in estate kitchens that prefer Italian aesthetic but don't want Zephyr Designer Series prices. Repair almost always favored over replacement on this tier given the price gap, similar to repair economics on premium brands.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Power Pack Inserts (QP3 Series)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">QP3 series · custom hood applications</p>
        <p>Used when a customer wants a custom decorative hood (wood, copper, plaster, custom millwork) with Broan internals doing the actual ventilation work. The QP3 insert lives inside the custom enclosure. Service approach differs from standard hood work — the technician has to access the custom enclosure first before reaching the Broan internals, which adds 15-25% to typical labor time. Custom hood owners often don't realize there's a Broan unit inside until service is needed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>NuTone Vintage Units (Legacy 1980s-2000s)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">NL630 · RL6230 · NuTone-Broan dual-branded transition era</p>
        <p>NuTone discontinued range hood production but the legacy units still run in older LA homes — Hancock Park, Westwood, Culver City, parts of Studio City, and other neighborhoods with substantial pre-2000 housing stock. We service these where possible: light sockets, basic switches, and bulbs we can keep going indefinitely. Control electronics and full motor assemblies on NuTone units are increasingly hard to source — we'll quote what we can but most repair conversations on 20+ year NuTone units include a 5-year replacement-planning horizon.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 COMMON FAILURES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, What goes wrong</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Broan range hood failure patterns we see most often.</h2>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Fan motor seizure (most common, predictable across all series):</strong> 40000 Series typical lifespan 5-8 years; 41000 Series 7-10; Allure 8-12; Evolution 10-15. Replacement runs $180-$280 with labor. The honest framing varies by series: on 40000 Series 8+ years old, replacement units at $120-$150 retail are often cheaper than the repair. On Evolution and Best by Broan, repair wins clearly.</li>
      <li><strong>Two-speed switch wear (40000 and 41000 Series):</strong> Mechanical switch fatigue from high-frequency use in active kitchens. Symptoms: switch sticky, won't move to high speed, fan stuck on one speed. $80-$130 with labor. DIY-able for a confident homeowner with basic tools.</li>
      <li><strong>Light socket and bulb issues:</strong> Older units used halogen bulbs; broken sockets from previous removal attempts are common. Newer LED units have fewer issues but socket failures still happen at 10+ years. $60-$110 with labor. We always check the full light circuit during any service call — it's common to see two or three sockets failing simultaneously after a decade.</li>
      <li><strong>Filter clogging (maintenance, not repair):</strong> Aluminum mesh filters with model-specific sizing. Routine annual cleaning prevents most performance issues. We include filter assessment in every service call — frequently the "reduced cooling performance" complaint resolves through filter cleaning at no parts charge.</li>
      <li><strong>Touchpad and control panel failures (Allure and Evolution):</strong> Newer Broan electronics carry a different failure profile from the basic 40000 Series. Replacement control panels run $200-$380. On Allure mid-tier, replacing the whole unit sometimes makes more economic sense than investing in a control board repair; on Evolution, the unit value justifies the repair.</li>
      <li><strong>Vent cover misalignment and ducted/ductless conversion issues:</strong> Installation issues, not unit faults — common after kitchen renovations done by general contractors. $80-$150 to align and seal properly, or to install the correct recirculating filter.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Recent repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Broan jobs from across the territory.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Four representative service calls across the Broan lineup. Names and addresses omitted; technical scenarios are typical of what we see.</p>

    <div class="repair-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>40000 Series volume service, Mid-Wilshire apartment building</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> 24-unit apartment building had six similar fan-motor failures over a two-month window. Property manager called for bulk service. Units were 7 years old, all 403004 stainless under-cabinet 30-inch.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Predictable fan motor seizure pattern at the 5-8 year mark for 40000 Series. Property manager preferred repair over replacement to maintain unit consistency across the building.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Bulk motor replacement on six units same-day. We coordinated parts supply and routed a single tech through the building.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $145 per unit, $870 total. Volume discount applied for 4+ unit same-property work.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Evolution 3, Sherman Oaks residential remodel</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> 5-year-old Evolution 3 36-inch wall-mount with the touchpad responding intermittently after a summer 2025 power surge.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Control board partial failure from the surge event. WhispAire fan controls testing within spec; the fault was specifically on the control side.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> OEM Broan control board replacement, full WhispAire fan recalibration, verified all control functions across a test cycle. Customer specifically chose Evolution for quiet operation; the repair preserved that benefit instead of forcing a downgrade to basic 41000 Series.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $385 total. About 80 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Best by Broan, Beverly Hills estate kitchen</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> 9-year-old Best by Broan Italian premium with motor noise increasing over several months. Customer reported the noise developed gradually and was now noticeable during quiet conversations in the adjacent dining area.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Motor bearing wear from long-term use plus accumulated heat exposure. OEM Best parts route through specialty distribution rather than the broader Broan parts pipeline; 2-day wait disclosed upfront.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> OEM Best motor assembly replacement, full unit clean while the access was open. Quiet operation restored.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $420 total. Customer's $1,200+ retail unit saved through repair versus replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>NuTone NL630, Hancock Park 1985-built kitchen</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> 40-year-old NuTone NL630 with both interior light sockets failed. Halogen bulbs had corroded into the sockets over four decades, and previous DIY removal attempts had broken the socket threading.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Socket replacement plus LED retrofit was the only viable path — original halogen bulbs and sockets are increasingly hard to source for NL630.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Both sockets replaced with LED-compatible retrofits, LED bulbs installed (better light output than original halogen, longer service life). Honest framing for the customer: hood is mechanically fine for now, but parts pipeline for NL630 is increasingly limited; 5-year horizon for replacement planning.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $145 total including LED bulbs.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 LA CONTEXT -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05, Where we see Broan in LA</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Broan installs across Greater Los Angeles.</h2>

    <p>The Broan footprint across our LA service area is wider than any other ventilation brand we cover. <strong>Apartment buildings and multi-family housing</strong> in Mid-Wilshire, Koreatown, North Hollywood, and Van Nuys lean almost universally on 40000 and 41000 Series volume installs — building owners and property managers rotate units through tenant turnovers, and our volume service contracts cover several large-portfolio managers in these areas. <strong>Condo refurbs and tenant turnovers</strong> in WeHo and Mid-City run 40000 Series replacement volume.</p>

    <p><strong>Mid-tier residential remodels</strong> in Studio City, Sherman Oaks, Encino, and Northridge dominate with 41000 Series and Allure mid-tier installations spec'd 2015-2022. <strong>Builder-grade new construction</strong> in suburban LA and the Inland Empire valley runs 40000 and 41000 Series at builder spec. <strong>NuTone vintage units</strong> show up in older LA homes — Hancock Park, Westwood, Culver City, and similar neighborhoods with substantial pre-2000 housing stock; service work on these increasingly tilts toward replacement-planning conversations.</p>

    <p>Estate kitchens rarely run base Broan unless the install is Best by Broan (Italian premium), and even then we see Best by Broan less often than Zephyr Designer Series in true high-end LA kitchens. Broan's LA presence skews mid-tier and mass-market — and we do high volume of Broan service work through apartment building service contracts, often more individual unit visits per month than any other single brand combined.</p>
  </div>
</section>

